Morning (10:00:00) in the Restricted Archives—you pause in your examination of the mysterious tome and take a proper look around the chamber.

The Restricted Archives stretch before you in a cathedral of knowledge, though one that has seen better centuries. Towering oak shelves, blackened with age, rise fifteen feet to the vaulted ceiling, their ledges thick with accumulated dust. Faded tapestries depicting ancient scholars debating cosmic truths line the walls between towering bookshelves, their threads unraveling toward the floor.

Three reading tables of heavy mahogany sit scattered about, their surfaces scarred by centuries of quill and ink. Brass fixtures that once held candles now stand empty, their light source long since extinguished. The stained glass windows—your only illumination—depict scenes of cosmic creation, though several panes are missing cracked or entirely, allowing drafts to whisper through the chamber.

The air itself feels heavy, tasting of mildew and something older, stranger—like the dust of dead languages. Your footsteps echo with surprising loudness on the worn flagstone floor, and you notice the shadows seem deeper here than they should be, as if the light struggles to penetrate the accumulated silence of centuries.

To your left, a narrow doorway leads further into the archives. Behind you, the passage back to the main library. And directly before you, the mysterious tome continues its faint pulsing glow, its alien symbols seemingly shifting when viewed from the corner of your eye.

The Scholar (Lvl 1 Wizard) stands in the center of this forgotten chamber, spell components at the ready, scholarly curiosity warring with understandable caution.

